- There are roughly two approaches to turning an isSCM into an iSCM:
  1) work with subprobability measures (normalization <= 1); Patrick points out that this may give rise to issues when looking at marginal probabilities because 
     if the marginal is defined as integrating out some part (in the conventional way) probability may 'leak', so then the X2-marginal of p(X_2|X_1) \otimes p(X_1)
     is not =p(X_2) but <=p(X_2). A way out, proposed by Patrick, is to represent the subprobability measures as probability measures on an extended space which has one additional point
     (so it is a mixture component where the other component represents the 'leaked' samples). Then you can stick to the default operations.
  2) just avoid talking about interventions that would lead to 0 samples under the selection mechanism; for that you can restrict the range of the input nodes, but in addition you still have to add a qualifier for any additional intervention that you contemplate
  It's an intriguing question whether the 'expressiveness' of the first approach would be slightly larger than that of the second approach, because the isSCM can actually predict that under certain observations we'll see 0 samples

