- check whether we really anywhere need to interpret an exogenous random variable as causal; I guess one can always workaround in that case by making an endogenous copy.
  So indeed it makes sense to interpret all exogenous random variables as \emph{non-causal}. This then changes the terminology of common cause (9.3) and we should rename this into `confounder'; on the other hand, `confounder' is a slippery object so perhaps it's even better to call it `confounding'. Only for endogenous variables can we then speak about common causes. This allows to interpret bidirected edges as dependencies introduced by latent pre-interventional selection/conditioning, or as introduced by a common cause. This should fix the issues with 9.3 and higher.
