- regarding reductions: it seems one can formulate a general notion of reduction for a CBN. First, one can bring
it into standard form, such that each latent is parent of at least two observed nodes, and each latent is exogenous.
For each latent, one can then apply the reduction trick to any node in its set of children
that is not a descendant of another child (there is always at least one such node, but there could be multiple, 
which allows one to choose one e.g. the one with smallest cardinality).
This also allows us to construct a canonical CBN given a CADMG and the spaces of the observed nodes, which can
be constructed to be interventionally equivalent to any CBN with that observational CADMG.

- idea for Simpson's paradox: to make it easier to setup exercises in which Simpson's paradox happens,
one can use (for Z confounder, X cause and Y effect) the parameterization 
 p(x,y,z) = \exp(\zeta z) \exp((\alpha + \beta z)x) \exp((\gamma + \delta x + \epsilon z)y)
Now take \delta < 0 (causal effect of x on y is negative), \zeta = 0 (for simplicity, or male/female situation),
\beta = \epsilon (for simplicity), \beta > -\delta + \log(2)/2 (to get a reversal).

- There is an inconsistency in the setup. To derive the Markov property for SCMs, we rely on the (weaker)
Markov property for CBNs. It is weaker in the sense that it is not able to distinguish between an endogenous 
node without parents (which must be constant) and an exogenous random variable, while in the SCM, we could.
But actually, something similar not only holds for "exogenous" nodes: it seems we could formulate a stronger
Markov property by using D-separation. The SCM graph does contain more information that can be exploited to
derive conditional independences. When marginalizing out all exogenous random nodes, this information is lost.
This also connects to definitions like 'confounder', where if we want a sharp definition, we want the confounder
to show variation (i.e. not be constant). 
One could decide to copy Geiger's graphical notation and introduce D-separation.
If not, it makes sense to assume that there are no endogenous variables without parents, i.e., every
'output' variable without parents is an exogenous random variable.
Still, then, we can have exogenous random variables that are a.s. constant and not recognized as such.
Also, one might want to add a cleanup operation to remove constant parts of an SCM. But then, do we always
cleanup after some operation (like intervention)? Then we no longer have commutation, as this information is
not present in the graph. Or we should add it to the graph. But then the whole formalism becomes much heavier still.
So this seems overkill.
This point also interacts with the chosen quantifiers: ideally, we would like to have 
``for all x_J, for almost all x_W, for all x_V'' but then we should not allow interventions on W variables.
So this might make sense if we start to distinguish intervenable and non-intervenable variables as well.
Which will also make the formalism much heavier.
I guess there will always be subtle information in the model specification that we don't want to add to the
graph; so if one demands commutativity/compatibility we have to make choices.
One also sees this with the definition of confounder/confounding: our notion of confounding implies exchangeability,
but not vice versa.
This, by the way, is not actually that different from the definition of (direct) cause: that also does not imply
necessarily identifiability from observational or interventional data.

